{{Use British English|date=February 2015}}
| honorific_prefix    = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berbahagia Datuk]]
| honorific_suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=MYS|size=100%|PJN}}
[[Malay titles#Datuk|Datuk]] '''Paul Low Seng Kuan''' ({{lang-zh|t=劉勝權|s=刘胜权|j=Lau4 Sing3 Kyun4|poj=Lâu Sèng-koân|p=Liú Shèngquán}}) is a<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/05/23/i-was-helpless-when-they-were-transferred-says-paul-low/|title = I was helpless when they were transferred, says Paul Low | date=23 May 2018 }}</ref> [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]] [[Dewan Negara|Senator]] and former [[Minister in the Prime Minister's Department]]. He was the president of a non-governmental organisation called Transparency International - Malaysia (TI-M) until 24 May 2013. The organisation is a chapter of [[Transparency International]] (TI) - a world renowned anti-corruption NGO.<ref>Official Website.[http://www.transparency.org.my/ "Transparency Malaysia"], ''[[Transparency International]]'', Retrieved on 20 May 2013.</ref> After the 13th Malaysian general elections, Paul was appointed a Senator and a Minister in the Prime Minister's Department of Malaysia.<ref>News.[http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2013/5/16/nation/13118293&sec=nation "Paul Low: Government committed to tackling graft"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516172100/http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=%2F2013%2F5%2F16%2Fnation%2F13118293&sec=nation |date=16 May 2013 }}, ''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]'', 16 May 2013. Retrieved on 20 May 2013.</ref> His portfolio involved collaborating with relevant stakeholders including federal ministries and state governments to promote good governance practice and strengthening of transparency and accountability.

